                    Synaxis 2.2.0 Installation

Requirements:
  - GCC 10+ (tested with GCC 15)
  - GNU Make, autoconf, automake
  - OpenSSL 1.1+ or 3.x (libssl-dev)
  - libsodium (libsodium-dev)
  - libargon2 (libargon2-dev)
  - TRE regex library (libtre-dev)
  - GeoIP library (libgeoip-dev)
  - Python 3.x (optional, for mod-python)

Build:
  autoreconf -fi
  ./configure --prefix=$HOME/services \
    --enable-modules=blacklist,botserv,helpserv,hostserv,\
    memoserv,no,python,qserver,snoop,sockcheck,track,webtv
  make -j$(nproc)
  make install

This installs:
  $HOME/services/bin/x3          - the binary
  $HOME/services/etc/x3.conf     - default config (edit this)
  $HOME/services/share/x3/       - help files, plugins
  $HOME/services/var/x3/         - database files (runtime)

Configuration:
  Edit $HOME/services/etc/x3.conf to set:
  - Uplink address/port/password (must match Cathexis ircd.conf)
  - Server name and numeric
  - Service bot nicks
  - TLS settings (optional)

  See x3.conf.example for all options.

Cathexis IRCd Setup:
  In your Cathexis ircd.conf, add a Connect block:
    Connect {
      name = "services.your.network";
      host = "127.0.0.1";
      password = "link_password";
      port = 4400;
      class = "Server";
    };
    UWorld {
      name = "services.your.network";
    };

Running:
  $HOME/services/bin/x3 -f    # foreground (testing)
  $HOME/services/bin/x3       # daemonize (production)

Signals:
  SIGINT  (Ctrl-C) - Save databases and exit
  SIGQUIT (Ctrl-\) - Save databases only
  SIGHUP           - Rehash (reload configuration)

After First Start:
  The first IRC operator to /oper up and register with NickServ
  gets root (level 1000) access. Use:
    /msg NickServ REGISTER <account> <password>

Support:
  https://github.com/brandontroidl/Synaxis
  https://github.com/brandontroidl/Cathexis
